Ra: The ancient Egyptian deity of the Sun, identified primarily with the noon-day sun. Ra ruled in all parts of the created world: the sky, the Earth, and the underworld. He was believed to have ruled as the first pharaoh of Ancient Egypt and was the god of the sun, order, kings, and the sky. Ra was portrayed as a falcon and shared characteristics with the sky-god Horus.  
Anubis: The god of funerary rites, protector of graves, and guide to the underworld. Anubis was depicted as a canine or a man with a canine head. He was a protector of graves and an embalmer, and he attended the weighing scale during the "Weighing of the Heart" to determine if a soul could enter the realm of the dead.  
Horus: A sky god associated with kingship and the sun. Horus was often depicted as a falcon or a man with a falcon's head. He was the son of Osiris and Isis and was a central figure in the Osiris myth, representing the rightful king of Egypt.  
Isis: A goddess of magic, motherhood, and fertility. Isis was the wife of Osiris and mother of Horus. She was a powerful magician and was revered as a protective goddess, especially of the dead.  
Osiris: The god of the afterlife, the underworld, and the dead. Osiris was the husband of Isis and father of Horus. He was murdered by his brother Set but was resurrected by Isis, becoming the ruler of the underworld.  
Set: The god of chaos, storms, and the desert. Set was the brother of Osiris and the murderer of Osiris. He was often depicted as a chaotic force but was also a protector of Ra during his nightly journey through the underworld.  
Thoth: The god of wisdom, writing, and the moon. Thoth was often depicted as an ibis or a baboon. He was the scribe of the gods and was associated with the arbitration of disputes and the invention of writing.  
Hathor: The goddess of love, beauty, music, and motherhood. Hathor was often depicted as a cow or a woman with cow's horns. She was a protective goddess and was associated with joy and celebration.  
Bastet: The goddess of home, fertility, and childbirth, often depicted as a lioness or a cat. Bastet was a protective goddess and was associated with the home and domesticity.
